{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621510"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:54:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:54:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16749"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16749"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.18,0.32,0.09,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9440"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74842"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9440"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16749"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60348"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7166"},{"type":"tags","id":"7180"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22315"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74842"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department following a motor vehicle accident. During the neurological examination, you consider the anatomical relationship between the meninges and peripheral nerves.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the relationship between spinal nerve coverings and the meninges?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arachnoid mater fuses with perineurium","Pia mater fuses with endoneurium","Dura mater fuses with epineurium","Arachnoid mater fuses with epineurium","Pia mater fuses with perineurium"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe meningeal layers have specific relationships with peripheral nerve coverings as nerves exit the spinal canal. \u003Cstrong\u003EDura mater fuses with epineurium\u003C/strong\u003E of spinal nerves as they pass through the intervertebral foramina. This anatomical relationship is important for understanding the spread of infection and local anaesthetic agents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Earachnoid mater fuses with perineurium\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the arachnoid layer terminates at the dorsal root ganglion and does not continue along peripheral nerves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epia mater fuses with endoneurium\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While the pia mater does continue along nerve roots, it does not specifically fuse with the endoneurium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Earachnoid mater fuses with epineurium\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the arachnoid mater does not extend beyond the dorsal root ganglion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epia mater fuses with perineurium\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The perineurium is a distinct layer that surrounds fascicles of nerve fibres and is not continuous with the pia mater.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis anatomical knowledge is clinically relevant in procedures such as epidural anaesthesia and in understanding the potential spread of infections between the central nervous system and peripheral nerves.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The dura mater fuses with the epineurium of spinal nerves as they exit the intervertebral foramina.","The arachnoid mater terminates at the dorsal root ganglion and does not extend along peripheral nerves.","Understanding meningeal relationships to peripheral nerves is crucial for explaining the spread of infection and local anaesthetic."],"references":["Lu S, Brusic A, Gaillard F. Arachnoid Membranes: Crawling Back into Radiologic Consciousness. AJNR Am J Neuroradiol. 2022 Feb;43(2):167-175. doi: 10.3174/ajnr.A7309. Epub 2021 Oct 28. PMID: 34711549; PMCID: PMC8985673","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons.","Kekere V, Alsayouri K. Anatomy, Head and Neck, Dura Mater. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545301/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60348"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16749"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60348"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T20:50:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T21:02:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9440"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74842"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/ta